         <fw type="continued" place="right"><date> January 21st, 30 </date></fw>
         <fw type="continued" place="left"><name ref="pers:CGS1">Mr. C. Gardner Sullivan</name></fw>
         <fw type="continued" place="right"><name ref="pers:WE1">Winnifred Reeve</name></fw>
         <fw type="continued" place="left">cc to&#160;<name ref="pers:CL3">Mr. Carl Laemmle Jr</name>.</fw>
         <fw type="continued" place="center">RE: K by&#160;<name ref="pers:MRR1">Mary Roberts
               Rinehart</name>.</fw>
         <div>

            <p>This is a very fine story, a human and even dramatic tale. The characterizations are
               especially fine. Though it may be considered old fashioned, in my opinion there is no
               question but what a very fine picture could be made from this novel. Considerable
               adaptation will be necessary to make it up-to-date. But, tale n all in all although
               it is fifteen years old it nonetheless remains a grand story.</p>

            <p>Of course there is the question to consider whether we wish to do a picture that, to
               a large extent, is concerned with a hospital, surgery etc. for the main theme of the
               story is concerned with a great surgeon who has become a recluse on account of his
               supposed failure in a serious operation. And the main character is a nurse in the
               hospital; in fact a great deal of the action takes place in a hospital.</p>

            <p>Itâ€™s quite true that <q>K</q> may be considered as of the old school of writing to a
               certain extent, but the old formula is as good as ever under new treatment. </p>


         </div>
